Functional and non-functional requirements have two functions. 1) they name and describe the requirement and 2) they reference the requirement.

(public)
setting.definition: (pubic) refers to a public access point.

setting.name: (gov)
setting.definition: (gov) refers to a protected access point for reviewers, managers, approvers, help-desk, and system-administrators..

setting.name: (guest)
setting.definition: (guest) is a role that gives minimum access to the public system. This level of access allows an actor to initiate an account.

setting.name: (account)
setting.definition: (account) is the first privilege granted. This level of access allows an actor to complete the registration.

setting.name: (registrant)
setting.definition: (registrant) has completed his or her registration and can request NRN and ER privileges.

setting.name: (NRN)
setting.definition: (NRN) allow an actor to initiate new National Register Nominations

setting.name: (ER)
setting.definition: (ER) allow an actor to initiate new Environmental Reviews

setting.name: (editor)
setting.definition: (editor) gives an actor access to modify, and complete nominations and reviews. In addition, this role can invite other registrants to assist with the preparation process materials.

setting.name: (editor-proxy)
setting.definition: (editor-proxy) gives an actor access to modify a specific nomination or review.

setting.name: (reviewer)
setting.definition: (reviewer) gives access to read and make comments about a specific nomination or review.

setting.name: (help-desk)
setting.definition: (help-desk) gives an actor the ability to see the system from the perspective of another actor. This is meant to facilitate issue resolution via a phone conversation. This role can comment but not save.

task-button
setting.definition: gets values from the tsk_screen column in Tasks for current site-type, access-type, process-type and process-role-type, table name and the column defined in goto attribute. task-buttons should be named the same as the tsk_screen value and populate the goto attribute with the source field name i.e., tsk_screen. Field names should be unique. No need to define children. Associated Screens should be defined for each task and should have type overlay. Add data to the settings, stsk_role = the proper role, stsk_name = the target Screen.
